    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Mickey Moniak** (75.98) and **Corbin Carroll** (69.14) headline our offensive output. **Mickey Moniak** is our top-rated play, buoyed significantly by a favorable hitting environment and the +14% platoon boost against Freddy Peralta, while his position at the top of the order maximizes his run-scoring potential. **James Wood** (69.03) also earns a high recommendation, as his premier leadoff spot against Taj Bradley provides the volume necessary to remain an elite start despite the middling xERA of the opposing starter. Meanwhile, **Seiya Suzuki** (68.17) remains a high-floor play against Andrew Abbott, benefiting from an favorable park adjustment and his position in the heart of the order. While we are prioritizing speed, **Trevor Story** (60.77) and **Brice Turang** (65.04) are strong tactical starts, with their projected success against Framber Valdez and Andre Pallante respectively enhanced by the slow delivery times of both opposing pitchers, providing excellent opportunities for stolen bases.\n\nOur most difficult roster decision involved keeping **Austin Riley** (47.57) on the bench. Despite a solid pedigree, he fell below the efficiency threshold due to a difficult matchup against George Kirby and a negative park factor that dragged his composite score down, making him a marginal play compared to the higher-ceiling platoon advantages presented by **Vinnie Pasquantino** (67.53) and **Josh Naylor** (64.46). Risks remain throughout the lineup as we await official confirmations; **Tyler Soderstrom** (43.82) is flirting with our \"below floor\" category due to a significant -19% penalty from facing a tough arm in Cristopher S\u00e1nchez, though he stays in the lineup for now on the strength of the \"Wind Out\" factor. Investors should note that all starting spots are currently relying on assumed lineup positions; any downward shift in the batting order for **Dalton Rushing** or **Gabriel Moreno** could further suppress their already cautious scores.",
